[[File:Loosesocks-sobuline2011.jpg|thumbnail|Loose socks in Japan]]

{{nihongo|'''Loose socks'''|ルーズソックス|rūzu sokkusu}} are a style of baggy [[sock]] worn by [[Japanese people|Japanese]] high school girls, as part of ''[[kogal]]'' culture.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/721378/Filling-the-gap.html |title=Filling the gap |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |first=Sam |last=Wallace | location=London | date=24 October 1998 |accessdate=2010-05-11}}</ref> This style of socks has also become popular among American teens and college students who are fans of Japanese [[anime]] and [[manga]]. These socks come in a variety of styles—defined by the knitting pattern of the upper. The two most popular styles are the traditional 2×2 rib knit (pictured) and tube-style loose socks, which are thigh-high length tube socks worn pushed down around the ankles. 

They were adopted as a fashion which flattered plump calves and also expressed rebellious deviation from Japan's strict [[dress code]] for [[Japanese school uniform|school uniforms]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-iaiARtuCaIC&pg=PA810 |title=Japan: The Rough Guide |first=Jan |last=Dodd |author2=Simon Richmond  |publisher=Rough Guides |location=London |edition=1st |date=1999 |page=810 |isbn=9781858283401 |oclc=441275694}}</ref> It is used as an inspiration for photography by [[Akira Gomi]]. They are also used in Japanese fashions like Kogal and Fairy Kei.

